\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces Results of the power simulation. Power is defined as the average share of statistically significant effects within a study, across 1,000 simulated studies. The plot shows power as a function of sample size (n per experimental condition, with equal sample size assumed for all 20 treatment conditions, and twice as many for the control condition). The two curves represent non-adjusted vs.~adjusted p-values. The three facets represent different effect sizes.}}{18}{figure.caption.16}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig-power}{{2}{18}{Results of the power simulation. Power is defined as the average share of statistically significant effects within a study, across 1,000 simulated studies. The plot shows power as a function of sample size (n per experimental condition, with equal sample size assumed for all 20 treatment conditions, and twice as many for the control condition). The two curves represent non-adjusted vs.~adjusted p-values. The three facets represent different effect sizes}{figure.caption.16}{}}
